[{"data":1,"prerenderedAt":1154},["ShallowReactive",2],{"header-locale:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2024\u002F05\u002F01\u002Fjavascript-generate-uuid-in-browser-no-npm\u002F":3,"page:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2024\u002F05\u002F01\u002Fjavascript-generate-uuid-in-browser-no-npm\u002F":4,"alt:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2024\u002F05\u002F01\u002Fjavascript-generate-uuid-in-browser-no-npm\u002F":3,"prev-next:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2024\u002F05\u002F01\u002Fjavascript-generate-uuid-in-browser-no-npm\u002F":1130,"related:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2024\u002F05\u002F01\u002Fjavascript-generate-uuid-in-browser-no-npm\u002F":1139},"\u002Fjavascript\u002F20240501\u002F1138017174\u002F",{"id":5,"title":6,"abbrlink":7,"altUrl":3,"body":8,"category":1114,"date":1115,"description":1116,"extension":1117,"lang":1118,"meta":1119,"navigation":295,"path":1120,"readingMinutes":156,"seo":1121,"standalone":1122,"stem":1123,"tags":1124,"tldr":1127,"updated":1115,"url":1128,"__hash__":1129},"content\u002Fen\u002FJavaScript\u002Fjavascript-generate-uuid-in-browser-no-npm.md","Generate a UUID Right in the Browser — No npm Package Needed","1001457099",{"type":9,"value":10,"toc":1102},"minimark",[11,16,29,33,45,54,57,193,199,449,459,463,469,633,639,642,663,670,678,734,751,756,767,837,847,854,869,872,883,892,902,919,926,964,979,996,1003,1057,1060,1067,1084,1087,1098],[12,13,15],"h2",{"id":14},"intro","Intro",[17,18,19,20,24,25,28],"p",{},"When you're writing a blog post or putting together a quick demo, you almost always end up faking some data. And that fake data usually needs a unique value attached to it — the classic ",[21,22,23],"code",{},"key","\u002F",[21,26,27],{},"id",". So this post is about how to generate a unique key\u002Fid without reaching for any package at all.",[12,30,32],{"id":31},"whats-a-unique-keyid-anyway","What's a unique key\u002Fid anyway?",[17,34,35,36,38,39,41,42,44],{},"A unique value just means that within a collection, every element is one of a kind — no duplicates. In programming you'll see this value called a ",[21,37,23],{}," or an ",[21,40,27],{}," (I'll just call it ",[21,43,27],{}," from here on).",[17,46,47,48,50,51,53],{},"Bit abstract, right? Let's picture an example. Say we're building a TodoList, and every Todo has its own unique ",[21,49,27],{},". That ",[21,52,27],{}," is our unique value. Why do we need it? Because we use it to do things — delete a todo, update it, and so on.",[17,55,56],{},"So for a TodoList, the data is usually an array of objects, and it might look something like this:",[58,59,64],"pre",{"className":60,"code":61,"language":62,"meta":63,"style":63},"language-js shiki shiki-themes github-dark-high-contrast","const todos = [\n  { id: 1, text: 'Hello World', done: false },\n  { id: 2, text: 'Hello JavaScript', done: false },\n  { id: 3, text: 'Hello Vue.js', done: false },\n  { id: 4, text: 'Hello React.js', done: false },\n  { id: 5, text: 'Hello Angular.js', done: false },\n];\n","js","",[21,65,66,86,111,130,149,168,187],{"__ignoreMap":63},[67,68,71,75,79,82],"span",{"class":69,"line":70},"line",1,[67,72,74],{"class":73},"sWyjQ","const",[67,76,78],{"class":77},"sCcAr"," todos",[67,80,81],{"class":73}," =",[67,83,85],{"class":84},"sMAXC"," [\n",[67,87,89,92,95,98,102,105,108],{"class":69,"line":88},2,[67,90,91],{"class":84},"  { id: ",[67,93,94],{"class":77},"1",[67,96,97],{"class":84},", text: ",[67,99,101],{"class":100},"sTRMh","'Hello World'",[67,103,104],{"class":84},", done: ",[67,106,107],{"class":77},"false",[67,109,110],{"class":84}," },\n",[67,112,114,116,119,121,124,126,128],{"class":69,"line":113},3,[67,115,91],{"class":84},[67,117,118],{"class":77},"2",[67,120,97],{"class":84},[67,122,123],{"class":100},"'Hello JavaScript'",[67,125,104],{"class":84},[67,127,107],{"class":77},[67,129,110],{"class":84},[67,131,133,135,138,140,143,145,147],{"class":69,"line":132},4,[67,134,91],{"class":84},[67,136,137],{"class":77},"3",[67,139,97],{"class":84},[67,141,142],{"class":1